RenderingAxis.definition: A reference component of a plot or rendering of data. A plot typically is a 2-dimensional rendering with a horizontal and verticle axis. A third dimension can be introduced with a color coding of the rendered data.

RenderingHints.definition: Attributes to aid in the rendering of parameter.

Report.definition: A document which describes the findings of some individual or group.

Repository.definition: A location or facility where resources are stored.

RepositoryID.definition: The identifier of an Repository resource.

ResonanceSounder.definition: "A combination of a radio receiver and a pulsed transmitter used to study the plasma surrounding a spacecraft by identifying resonances or cut-offs (of the wave dispersion relation), whose frequencies are related to the ambient plasma density and magnetic field. When the transmitter is off it is essentially a high frequency-resolution spectral power receiver."

ResourceHeader.definition: Attributes of a resource which pertain to the provider of the resource and descriptive information about the resource.

ResourceID.definition: "A Resource ID is a URI that has the form ""scheme://authority/path"" where ""scheme"" is ""spase"" for those resources administered through the SPASE framework, ""authority"" is the unique identifier for the resource provider registered within the SPASE framework and ""path"" is the unique identifier of the resource within the context of the ""authority"". The resource ID must be unique within the SPASE framework."

ResourceName.definition: A short textual description of a resource which may be useful when read by a person.

Restricted.definition: Access to the product is regulated and requires some form of identification.

RetardingPotentialAnalyser.definition: An instrument which measures ion temperatures and ion concentrations using a planar ion trap.

RevisionOf.definition: A modified version of a resource instance.

Rhea.definition: The second-largest moon of Saturn and the ninth-largest moon in the Solar System.

Riometer.definition: An instrument which measure the signal strength in various directions of the galactic radio signals. Variations in these signals are influenced by solar flare activity and geomagnetic storm and substorm processes.

Role.definition: The assigned or assumed function or position of an individual.

RTN.definition: "Radial Tangential Normal. Typically centered at a spacecraft. Used for IMF and plasma V vectors. R (radial) axis is radially away from the Sun, T (tangential) axis is normal to the plane formed by R and the Sun's spin vector, positive in the direction of planetary motion. N (normal) is R x T."

S3_BUCKET.definition: "A container of objects that comply with the Amazon Simple Storage Service (S3) specifications. A bucket has a unique, user-assigned key (name). A bucket can contain any number of objects with an aggregate size of 5 gigabytes. A bucket may be accompanied by up to 2 kilobytes of metadata."

Saturn.definition: The sixth planet from the sun in our solar system.

SC.definition: Spacecraft - A coordinate system defined by the spacecraft geometry and/or spin. Often has Z axis parallel to spacecraft spin vector. X and Y axes may or may not corotate with the spacecraft. See SR and SR2 below.

Scalar.definition: A quantity that is completely specified by its magnitude and has no direction.

ScaleMax.definition: "The maximum value that the variable is expected to attain. Used, for example, by automated plotting software."

ScaleMin.definition: "The minimum value that the variable is expected to attain. Used, for example, by automated plotting software."

ScaleType.definition: "The scaling to apply to an axis. If this attribute is not present, linear scale should be assumed."

Scientist.definition: An individual who is an expert in the phenomenon and related physics represented by the resource.

ScintillationDetector.definition: An instrument which detects flouresences of a material which is excited by high energy (ionizing) electromagnetic or charged particle radiation.

SE.definition: "Solar Ecliptic - A heliocentric coordinate system where the Z axis is normal to the ecliptic plane, positive northward. X axis is positive towards the first point of Aries (from Earth to Sun at vernal equinox). Same as HAE above. See <http://nssdc.gsfc.nasa.gov/space/helios/coor_des.html>"

SearchCoil.definition: An instrument which measures the time variation of the magnetic flux threading a loop by measurement of the electric potential difference induced between the ends of the wire.

SectorBoundaryCrossing.definition: A sector boundary crossing is a transit by a spacecraft across the heliospheric current sheet separating the dominantly outward (away-from-the-sun) interplanetary magnetic field of one hemisphere of the heliosphere from the dominantly inward (toward-the-sun) polarity of the other hemisphere.  Such crossings have multi-day intervals of opposite IMF dominant polarities on either side.

Service.definition: A location or facility that can perform a well defined task.

Set.definition: A collection of items for a particular purpose.

SHA1.definition: "Secure Hash Algorithm (SHA), a 160-bit message digest algorithm developed by the NSA and described in Federal Information Processing Standard (FIPS) publication 180-1."

SHA256.definition: "Secure Hash Algorithm (SHA), a 256-bit message digest algorithm developed by the NSA and described in Federal Information Processing Standard (FIPS) publication 180-1."

Size.definition: "The number of elements in each dimension of a multi-dimensional array. A scalar has a size of 1. A multi-dimensional vector will have a size for each dimension. Note that the number of elements in the size of an N-dimensional array conveys the array's dimensionality while the product of those numbers conveys the total number of elements in the array. When size is used to describe a tensor it is the number of elements in the tensor. As such it has a limited set of values. A tensor of rank 1 has a size of 3, rank 2 a size of 9, rank 3 a size of 27 and rank n a size of 3^n."

SM.definition: "Solar Magnetic - A geocentric coordinate system where the Z axis is northward along Earth's dipole axis, X axis is in plane of z axis and Earth-Sun line, positive sunward. See Russell, 1971."

SoftXRays.definition: X-Rays with an energy range of 0.12 keV to 12 keV.

SolarFlare.definition: An explosive event in the Sun's atmosphere which produces electromagnetic radiation across the electromagnetic spectrum at multiple wavelengths from long-wave radio to the shortest wavelength gamma rays.

SolarUVFlux.definition: The amount of Ultraviolet energy originating from the Sun passing through a unit area in a unit time.

SolarWindExtreme.definition: Intervals of unusually large or small values of solar wind attributes such as flow speed and ion density.

SolidAngle.definition: Integration over the angle in three-dimensional space that an object subtends at a point.

SolidStateDetector.definition: "A detector of the charge carriers (electrons and holes) generated in semiconductors by energy deposited by gamma ray photons. Also known as a ""semiconductor detector""."

SonicMachNumber.definition: The ratio of the bulk flow speed to the speed of sound in the medium.

Sounder.definition: An instrument which measures the radiances from an object. A sounder may measure radiances at multiple spectral ranges.

SoundSpeed.definition: The speed at which sound travels through a medium.

Source.definition: The location and attributes of an object.

SourceType.definition: A characterization of the function or purpose of the source.

SouthAtlanticAnomalyRegion.definition: "The region where the Earth's inner van Allen radiation belt makes its closest approach to the planet's surface. The result is that, for a given altitude, the radiation intensity is higher over this region than elsewhere."

SpacecraftOrbitPlane.definition: "A coordinate system where X lies in the plane normal to and in the direction of motion of the spacecraft, Z is normal to this plane and Y completes the triad in a right-handed coordinate system."

SpacecraftPotentialControl.definition: An instrument to control the electric potential of a spacecraft with respect to the ambient plasma by emitting a variable current of positive ions.

Spase.definition: Space Physics Archive Search and Extract (SPASE). The outermost container or envelope for SPASE metadata. This indicates the start of the SPASE metadata.

Specification.definition: A detailed description of the requirements and other aspects of an object or component that may be used to develop an implementation.

Spectral.definition: Characterized as a range or continuum of frequencies

SpectralPowerReceiver.definition: "A radio receiver which determines the power spectral density of the electric or magnetic field, or both, at one or more frequencies."

SpectralRange.definition: The general term used to describe wavelengths or frequencies within a given span of values for those quantities.

Spectrogram.definition: The characterization of signal strengths as a function of frequency (or energy) and time.

Spectrometer.definition: An instrument that measures the component wavelengths of light (or other electromagnetic radiation) by splitting the light up into its component wavelengths.

Spectrum.definition: "The distribution of a characteristic of a physical system or phenomenon, such as the energy emitted by a radiant source, arranged in the order of wavelengths."

Spherical.definition: "A coordinate representation of a position vector or of a measured vector by its magnitude and two direction angles. The angles are relative to the base axes of the coordinate system used. Typically the angles are phi [azimuth angle, =arctan (j/i)] and theta, where theta may be a polar angle, arctan {[SQRT(i^2+j^2)]/k}, or an elevation angle, arctan [k/SQRT (i^2+j^2)]."

SR.definition: Spin Reference - A special case of a Spacecraft (SC) coordinate system for a spinning spacecraft. Z is parallel to the spacecraft spin vector. X and Y rotate with the spacecraft. See <http://cdpp.cnes.fr/00428.pdf>

SR2.definition: "Spin Reference 2 - A special case of a Spacecraft (SC) coordinate system for a spinning spacecraft. Z is parallel to the spacecraft spin vector. X is in the plane defined by Z and the spacecraft-Sun line, positive sunward. See <http://cdpp.cnes.fr/00428.pdf>"

SSE.definition: "Spacecraft Solar Ecliptic - A coordinate system used for deep space spacecraft, for example Helios. - X axis from spacecraft to Sun. Z axis normal to ecliptic plane, positive northward. Note: Angle between normals to ecliptic and to Helios orbit plane ~ 0.25 deg."

SSE_L.definition: "Selenocentric Solar Ecliptic.  The X axis points from the center of the Earth's moon to the sun, the Z axis is normal to the ecliptic plane, positive northward.  And the Y axis completes the right-handed set of axes."

StackPlot.definition: "A representation of data showing multiple sets of observations on a single plot, possibly offsetting each plot by some uniform amount."

StandardDeviation.definition: The square root of the average of the squares of deviations about the mean of a set of data. Standard deviation is a statistical measure of spread or variability.

StartDate.definition: The specification of a starting point in time.

Stoke's Parameters.definition: "A set of four parameters (usually called I,Q, U and V) which describe the polarization state of an electromagnetic wave propagating through space."

StopDate.definition: The specification of a stopping point in time.

Strahl.definition: "A distribution of particles concentrated in a narrow energy band. The band may be may be aligned with a secondary feature. For example, it may occur in a narrow cone aligned with the mean magnetic field direction. "

Stratosphere.definition: "The layer of the atmosphere that extends from the troposphere to about 30 km, temperature increases with height. The stratosphere contains the ozone layer."

StreamInteractionRegion.definition: "The region (SIR) where two solar wind streams, typically having differing characteristics and solar sources, abut up against (and possibly partially interpenetrate) each other."

Strong.definition: Highly likely given the available evidence. Considered in the range of 7-10 on a scale of 0-10.

Structure.definition: The organization and relationship of individual values within a quantity.

Substorm.definition: A process by which plasma in the magnetotail becomes energized at a fast rate.

Sun.definition: The star upon which our solar system is centered.

Superhalo.definition: "The part of an object or distribution surrounding some central body or distribution evident in a second break in the distribution function (e.g., a different power law).  It consists of a population at a higher energies than for a halo."

Support.definition: "Information useful in understanding the context of an observation, typically observed or measured coincidentally with a physical observation."

SupportQuantity.definition: A characterization of the support information.

Surface.definition: The outermost area of a solid object.

Symmetric.definition: Equal distribution about one or more axes.

TAR.definition: "A file format used to collate collections of files into one larger file, for distribution or archiving, while preserving file system information such as user and group permissions, dates, and directory structures. The format was standardized by POSIX.1-1988 and later POSIX.1-2001."

TeamLeader.definition: An individual who is the designated leader of an investigation.

TeamMember.definition: An individual who is a major participant in an investigation.

TechnicalContact.definition: An individual who can provide specific information with regard to the resource or supporting software

TechnicalNote.definition: "A document summarizing the performance and other technical characteristics of a product, machine, component, subsystem or software in sufficient detail to be used by an engineer or researcher."

Temperature.definition: A measure of the kinetic energy of random motion with respect to the average. Temperature is properly defined only for an equilibrium particle distribution (Maxwellian distribution).

TemporalDescription.definition: A characterization of the time over which the measurement was taken.

Tensor.definition: "A generalized linear ""quantity"" or ""geometrical entity"" that can be expressed as a multi-dimensional array relative to a choice of basis of the particular space on which it is defined."

Tethys.definition: The third largest moon of Saturn.

Text.definition: A sequence of characters which may have an imposed structure or organization.

ThermalPlasma.definition: "Measurements of the plasma in the energy regime where the most of the plasma occurs. May be the basic fluxes in the form of distribution functions or the derived bulk parameters (density, flow velocity, etc.)."

ThermalSpeed.definition: "For a Maxwellian distribution, the difference between the mean speed and the speed within which ~69% (one sigma) of all the members of the speed distribution occur."

Thermosphere.definition: "The layer of the atmosphere that extends from the Mesosphere to 640+ km, temperature increasing with height."

Thumbnail.definition: A small representation of an image which is suitable to infer what the full-sized imaged is like.

TIFF.definition: A binary format for still pictures. Tagged Image Format File (TIFF). Originally developed by Aldus and now controlled by Adobe.

TIIS.definition: "Kronian Solar Orbital - A coordinate system related to Saturn where X is anti-sunward, Y along the orbital velocity direction."

TimeOfFlight.definition: An instrument which measures the time it takes for a particle to travel between two detectors.

TimeSeries.definition: A representation of data showing a set of observations taken at different points in time and charted as a time series.

TimeSpan.definition: The duration of an interval in time.

Titan.definition: "The largest moon of Saturn and the second-largest moon in the Solar System,"

Titania.definition: The largest moon of Uranus and the eighth largest moon in the Solar System.

Topside.definition: The region at the upper most areas of the ionosphere.

Total.definition: The summation of quantities over all possible species.

TotalPressure.definition: In an MHD fluid it is the number density (N) times Boltzmann constant times the temperature in Kelvin.

Trace.definition: The sum of the elements on the main diagonal (the diagonal from the upper left to the lower right) of a square matrix.

TransitionRegion.definition: "A very narrow (<100 km) layer between the chromosphere and the corona where the temperature rises abruptly from about 8000 to about 500,000 K."

Troposphere.definition: "The lowest layer of the atmosphere which begins at the surface and extends to between 7 km (4.4 mi) at the poles and 17 km (10.6 mi) at the equator, with some variation due to weather factors."

UDF.definition: "Universal Data Format (UDF). The Optical Technology Storage Association's Universal Disk Format, based on ISO 13346. See <http://www.osta.org/specs/index.htm>"

Ultraviolet.definition: Photons with a wavelength range: 10 to 400 nm.

Umbriel.definition: The third largest and fourth most massive moon of Uranus.

Uncalibrated.definition: Duplicate data are removed from the data stream and data are time ordered. Values are not adjusted for any potential biases or external factors.

Uncertainty.definition: A statistically defined discrepancy between a measured quantity and the true value of that quantity that cannot be corrected by calculation or calibration.

Units.definition: "A description of the standardized measurement increments in which a value is specified. The description is represented as a mathematical phrase. Units should be represented by widely accepted representation. For example, units should conform to the International System of Units (SI) which is maintained by BIPM (Bureau International des Poids et Mesures (see <http://www.bipm.fr/> ) when appropriate or use tokens like ""Re"" to represent units of the Radius of the Earth. Within a phrase the circumflex (^) is used to indicate a power, a star (*) is used to indicate multiplication and a slash (/) division. When symbols are not separated by a mathematical operator, multiplication is assumed. Symbols for base units can be found at: <http://www.bipm.fr/en/si/si_brochure/chapter2/2-1/#symbols> and those for common derived units can be found at: <http://www.bipm.fr/en/si/derived_units/2-2-2.html>"

UnitsConversion.definition: "The multiplicative factor for converting a unit into International System of Units (SI) units. The factor is expressed in the form ""number > x"", where ""number"" is a numerical value and ""x"" is the appropriate SI units. The basic SI units are Enumerated: m (meter), N (newton), kg (kilogram), Pa (pascal), s (second), Hz (hertz), A (ampere), V (volt), K (kelvin), W (watt), rad (radian), J (joule), sr (steradian), C (coulomb), T (tesla), ohm (ohm), mho (mho or seimens), H (henry), and F (farad). Two useful units which are not SI units are: degree (angle), and unitless (no units). An example is: ""1.0E-9>T"" which converts the units, presumable nT, to Tesla. Another example is: ""1.0e+3>m/s"" which converts a velocity expressed in kilometers per second to meters per second."

Unlikely.definition: Not likely given the available evidence. Considered in the range of 0 on a scale of 0-10.

Unspecified.definition: A value which is not provided.

Uranus.definition: The eighth planet from the sun in our solar system.

URL.definition: "Uniform Resource Locator (URL) is the global address of documents and other resources on the World Wide Web. The first part of the address indicates what protocol to use, and the second part specifies the IP address or the domain name where the resource is located followed by the pathname of the resource. A URL is specified in the form protocol://server.domain.name:port/pathname. Example protocols are HTTP or FTP, server domain name is the Internet name."

ValueFormat.definition: A string defining the output format used when extracting data values out to a file or screen. The magnitude and the number of significant figures needed should be carefully considered. The output format string can be in either Fortran or C syntax.

Variance.definition: A measure of dispersion of a set of data points around their mean value. The expectation value of the squared deviations from the mean.

VCrossB.definition: The cross product of the charge velocity (V) and the magnetic field (B). It is the electric field exerted on a point charge by a magnetic field.

Vector.definition: "A set of parameter values each along some independent variable (e.g., components of a field in three orthogonal spatial directions; atmospheric temperature values at several altitudes, or at a given latitude and longitude;)."

Velocity.definition: "Rate of change of position. Also used for the average velocity of a collection of particles, also referred to as ""bulk velocity""."

Venus.definition: The second planet from the sun in our solar system.

Version.definition: "Indicates the release identifier. When used to indicate the release of the SPASE data model, it is a in the form Major.Minor.Fix where Major: A significant change in the architecture of the model or rewrite of the implementation. This includes major changes in design or implementation language. This number starts at 0 (zero). Minor: An addition of terms or features that require changes in documentation/external API. This number starts at 0 (zero). Fix: Any change that doesn't require documentation/external API changes. This number starts at 0 (zero)."

Vertical.definition: Perpendicular to the plane of the horizon or a base line.

VOTable.definition: A proposed IVOA standard designed as a flexible storage and exchange format for tabular data.

VSO.definition: "Venus Solar Orbital - A coordinate system related to Venus where X is anti-sunward, Y along the orbital velocity direction."

Wave.definition: "Periodic or quasi-periodic (AC) variations of physical quantities in time and space, capable of propagating or being trapped within particular regimes."

WaveForm.definition: Spatial or temporal variations of wave amplitude over wave-period timescales.

WaveformReceiver.definition: A radio receiver which outputs the value of one or more components of the electric and/or magnetic field as a function of time.

Wavelength.definition: The peak-to-peak distance over one wave period.

WavelengthRange.definition: The range of possible values for the observed wavelength.

WaveQuantity.definition: A characterization of the physical properties of a wave.

Waves.definition: "Data resulting from observations of wave experiments and natural wave phenomena. Wave experiments are typically active and natural wave phenomena are passive. Examples of wave experiments include coherent/incoherent scatter radars, radio soundings, VLF propagation studies, ionospheric scintillation of beacon satellite signals, etc. Examples of natural wave phenomena include micropulsations, mesospheric gravity waves, auroral/plasmaspheric hiss, Langmuir waves, AKR, Jovian decametric radiation, solar radio bursts, etc."

WaveType.definition: A characterization of the carrier or phenomenon of wave information observed by the measurement.

Weak.definition: Slightly likely given the available evidence. Considered in the range of 1-4 on a scale of 0-10.

WGS84.definition: "The World Geodetic System (WGS) defines a reference frame for the earth, for use in geodesy and navigation. The WGS84 uses the zero meridian as defined by the Bureau International de l'Heure."

WhiteLight.definition: Photons with a wavelength in the visible range for humans.

WhitePaper.definition: An authoritative report giving information or proposals on an issue.

XML.definition: eXtensible Mark-up Language (XML). A structured format for representing information. See <http://www.w3.org/XML/>

XRays.definition: Photons with a wavelength range: 0.001 <= x < 10 nm

ZIP.definition: An open standard for compression which is a variation of the LZW method and was originally used in the PKZIP utility.

AccessRights.name: AccessRights
AccessRights.definition: Identifiers for permissions granted or denied by the host of a product to allow other users to access and use the resource.

AnnotationType.name: AnnotationType
AnnotationType.definition: Identifiers for an classification of an annotation.

Availability.name: Availability
Availability.definition: Identifiers for indicating the method or service which may be used to access the resource.

ClassificationMethod.name: ClassificationMethod
ClassificationMethod.definition: Identifiers for the technique used to determine the characteristics of an object.

Component.name: Component
Component.definition: Identifiers for the axis of coordinate systems.

ConfidenceRating.name: ConfidenceRating
ConfidenceRating.definition: Identifiers for the classification of the certainty of an assertion.

CoordinateRepresentation.name: CoordinateRepresentation
CoordinateRepresentation.definition: Identifiers of the method or form for specifying a given point or vector in a given coordinate system.

CoordinateSystemName.name: CoordinateSystemName
CoordinateSystemName.definition: Identifiers of the origin and orientation of a set of typically orthogonal axes.

DirectionAngle.name: DirectionAngle
DirectionAngle.definition: Identifiers for the angle between a vector and a base axis.

DisplayType.name: DisplayType
DisplayType.definition: Identifiers for types or classes of rendered data.

DocumentType.name: DocumentType
DocumentType.definition: Identifiers for the characterization of the content or purpose of a document.

Earth.name: Earth
Earth.definition: Identifiers for the regions surrounding the Earth.

Encoding.name: Encoding
Encoding.definition: Identifiers for unambiguous rules that establishes the representation of information within a file.

FieldQuantity.name: FieldQuantity
FieldQuantity.definition: Identifiers for the physical attribute of the field.

Format.name: Format
Format.definition: Identifiers for data organized according to preset specifications.

Hardcopy.name: Hardcopy
Hardcopy.definition: Identifiers for permanent reproductions, or copy in the form of a physical object, of any media suitable for direct use by a person.

HashFunction.name: HashFunction
HashFunction.definition: Identifiers for functions or algorithms that convert a digital data object into a hash value.

Heliosphere.name: Heliosphere
Heliosphere.definition: Identifiers for regions of the solar atmosphere which extends roughly from the inner corona to the edge of the solar plasma at the heliopause separating primarily solar plasma from interstellar plasma.

InstrumentType.name: InstrumentType
InstrumentType.definition: Identifiers for the type of experiment the instrument performs. This is the technique of observation.

Integral.name: Integral
Integral.definition: Identifiers for values above a given threshold and over area or solid-angle range.

Jupiter.name: Jupiter
Jupiter.definition: Identifiers for the regions surrounding the planet Jupiter.

Magnetosphere.name: Magnetosphere
Magnetosphere.definition: Identifiers for the region of space above the atmosphere or surface of the planet, and bounded by the magnetopause, that is under the direct influence of planet's magnetic field.

Mars.name: Mars
Mars.definition: Identifiers for the regions surrounding the planet Mars.

MeasurementType.name: MeasurementType
MeasurementType.definition: Identifiers for the method of making an estimated value of a quantity that forms the basis of an observation.

Mercury.name: Mercury
Mercury.definition: Identifiers for the regions surrounding the planet Mercury.

MixedQuantity.name: MixedQuantity
MixedQuantity.definition: Identifiers for the combined attributes of a mixed parameter quantity.

NearSurface.name: NearSurface
NearSurface.definition: Identifiers for regions of the gaseous and possibly ionized environment of a body extending from the surface to some specified altitude.

Neptune.name: Neptune
Neptune.definition: Identifiers for the regions surrounding the planet Neptune.

ParticleQuantity.name: ParticleQuantity
ParticleQuantity.definition: Identifiers for the characterization of the physical properties of the particle.

ParticleType.name: ParticleType
ParticleType.definition: Identifiers for the characterization of the kind of particle observed by the measurement.

PhenomenonType.name: PhenomenonType
PhenomenonType.definition: Identifiers for the characteristics or categorization of an observation. Note: Joe King to provide.

ProcessingLevel.name: ProcessingLevel
ProcessingLevel.definition: Identifiers to characterize the amount and type of manipulation which has been applied to the sampled data.

Projection.name: Projection
Projection.definition: Identifiers to projections into a coordinate system.

Qualifier.name: Qualifier
Qualifier.definition: Identifiers for terms which refine the type or attribute of a quantity.

Region.name: Region
Region.definition: Identifiers for areas of the physical world which may be occupied or observed.

RenderingAxis.name: RenderingAxis
RenderingAxis.definition: Identifiers for the reference component of a plot or rendering of data.

Role.name: Role
Role.definition: Identifiers for the assigned or assumed function or position of an individual.

Saturn.name: Saturn
Saturn.definition: Identifiers for the regions surrounding the planet Saturn.

ScaleType.name: ScaleType
ScaleType.definition: Identifiers for scaling applied to a set of numbers.

SourceType.name: SourceType
SourceType.definition: Identifiers for the characterization of the function or purpose of a source.

SpectralRange.name: SpectralRange
SpectralRange.definition: Identifiers for names associated with wavelengths. Based on the ISO 21348 Solar Irradiance Standard. Additions have been made to extend the frequency ranges to include those used in space physics. Those additions are indicated in blue text. The "Total Solar Irradiance" category has not been included since it is a type of measurement and not a specific spectral range. See Appendix A - Comparison of Spectrum Domains for a comparison of the spectral ranges with other systems.

Sun.name: Sun
Sun.definition: Identifiers for regions of the star upon which our solar system is centered.

SupportQuantity.name: SupportQuantity
SupportQuantity.definition: Identifiers for the information useful in understanding the context of an observation, typically observed or measured coincidentally with a physical observation.

Text.name: Text
Text.definition: Identifiers for the encoding of sequences of characters.

Venus.name: Venus
Venus.definition: Identifiers for the regions surrounding the planet Venus.

WaveQuantity.name: WaveQuantity
WaveQuantity.definition: Identifiers for the characterization of the physical properties of a wave.

WaveType.name: WaveType
WaveType.definition: Identifiers for the carrier or phenomenum of wave information observed by the measurement.

Waves.name: Waves
Waves.definition: Identifiers for experimental and natural wave phenomena.
